@NODE Utilisation

@{U}Rappel@{UU} : ARexx must be running.

Like it is an ARexx script, differents call modes are the followings :

> Rx AutoCat
> Rx AutoCat.rexx
> AutoCat.rexx       (Under OS 2.04+ and if protection flag « S » is set.)

Syntax:

Rx AutoCat Source [Destination] [Options]

 - Source : The file to process.

 - Destination : The description file to make. If it is missing, choose name
   will be the source one.
   An `.cd' extension is add if not already exists.

 - Options : Options begins with minus sign « - » et @{B}MUST be stick@{UB} between
   them when more one option.

@{B}Available options :@{UB}

    -e = Force the progy to continue same if errors encounters.
	 All errors were display instead of stop the process at the first
	 error.

    -w0 = Desactive the writing mode. Source file is handle but the
	  description file isn't wrote. It is a test mode to check the
	  source file before to make the final one.

    -# = Avoid to numbering labels. (0//) (1//) ...
	 Strings labels will not use the digit index so you must'nt use
	 this option if the index numbers isn't in continue and use some
	 skips! Also respect the chronologie!

Examples of use :

 AutoCat MyProg test
	 -> Will make the file « test.cd » exept if an error occurs.

 AutoCat MyProg test.cd -e
	 -> Will make the file « test.cd » and will show all errors.

 AutoCat MyProg -e-w0
	 -> Will show all errors found but no make the description file.

  AutoCat MyProg
	 -> Will make the file « MyProg.cd » exept if error.


@{B}Another way how it works :@{UB}

 Since version 1.1 AutoCat manage the `$VER_Strings:' option inside the
 source file. When AutoCat encounters ` ... $VER_Strings: x.y ...' it
 considers x.y as the version number of strings and it will be set to the
 description file.

 Example: /* $VER_Strings: 1.3  Version of my source strings */
 will create the following comment inside the description file:
 ; --  From description file version : 1.3

 Strings and labels can now be placed in any order.

 But label's odrer in description file will be the same than index labels
 source order! So respect 0, 1, 2, 3 ... order with -# option!

 @{U}Examples (good)@{UU}:
    Strings.0 = "** AutoCat **"
    MSG_Titre = 0

    MSG_Oui_Non = 1
    Strings.1 = "Yes|No"

 Using comments behind labels strings in source is permit:

 MSG_xx1 = 2   /* This is a comment */
 ...
 MSG_xx2 = 5   /* Do not cut this string */
 ...

 During analize of source file, this comments will be display on screen
 under this form:

> Commentaire (ligne °127) = "Ceci est un commentaire"
> Commentaire (ligne °130) = "Ne pas couper cette chaîne"

 Line numbers refer to line of comment in source ; only "MSG_..." comment
 will be displayed, not all source comments. :)

